form “ethnic squads” to the use of deportation and federal immigration restrictions to control local crime—even the introduction of fingerprinting—were motivated by attempts to govern a multiracial city. Campaigns to remake the police department created an urban landscape where power, gender, sexuality, race, ethnicity, crime, and bodies collided and provided a foundation for the supposedly color-blind, technocratic, federally backed, and surveillance-based policing of today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDiscrimination in law enforcementzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aLaw enforcementzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aPolice brutalityzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aPolicezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aPolice-community relationszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aRacial profiling in law enforcementzNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027546?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027546423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027546/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles